unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="369" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1797]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1412,1437]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName box="[582,667,1413,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astictus">
<emphasis box="[582,667,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">astictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (from Latin, meaning unspotted) refers to male proctiger lacking a pair of blackish dots laterally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="369" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1797]" box="[199,654,1484,1509]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1484,1509]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,1484,1509]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">China</collectingCountry>
(Sichuan) (
<figureCitation box="[557,641,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 84" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1006,1028]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,202,978]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,984]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 84. Geographical distribution of Metrocoris spp. in this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269723/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">
Fig. 
<number box="[609,641,1484,1508]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" value="84.0">84</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1797]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,428,1519,1544]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[446,665,1520,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astictus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[446,665,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">Metrocoris astictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[674,766,1519,1544]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[674,766,1519,1544]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
fits the diagnostic characters of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1192,1328,1520,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lituratus">
<emphasis box="[1192,1328,1520,1544]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">M. lituratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen" box="[277,530,1556,1581]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" refString="Chen, P. P. &amp; Nieser, N. (1993) A taxonomic revision of the Oriental water strider genus Metrocoris Mayr (Hemiptera, Gerridae). Part I &amp; II. Steenstrupia, 19, 1 - 43, 45 - 82." type="journal article" year="1993">
Chen &amp; Nieser (
<number box="[460,521,1556,1580]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" value="1993.0">1993</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The general appearance of the paramere in this new species is slightly similar to that of another new species 
<taxonomicName box="[462,645,1592,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guizhouensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[462,645,1592,1616]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">M. guizhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[652,741,1591,1616]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[652,741,1591,1616]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see below), with both occurring in the southern region of the Sichuan Basin. However, the paramere blade of 
<taxonomicName box="[693,816,1629,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astictus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[693,816,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">M. astictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[824,914,1628,1653]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[824,914,1628,1653]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is much more slender and slightly subapically curved (
<figureCitation box="[242,335,1663,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 66" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[187,1400,1438,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[175,1411,1430,1932]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 66. Paramere of Metrocoris spp. (males) in external view. 59 – 62. M. sichuanensis Chen &amp; Nieser, 1993 (59: Qingchen mountain; 60: Laojun mountain; 61: Xinmin village; 62: Hubaoxia Forest Park); 63. M. astictus sp. nov.; 64. M. falciformis sp. nov.; 65. M. guizhouensis sp. nov.; 66. M. zhengi sp. nov.. Scale 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269720/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">Figs. 63</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[347,378,1664,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES 72 – 83" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1842,1864]" captionTargetBox="[209,1373,887,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[205,1381,876,1821]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 72 – 83. Illustrations of endosoma sclerites (dorsal and lateral views) and paramere of Metrocoris spp. (males). 72 – 74. M. astictus sp. nov.; 75 – 77. M. falciformis sp. nov.; 78 – 80. M. guizhouensis sp. nov.; 81 – 83. M. zhengi sp. nov.. Scale 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269722/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">74</figureCitation>
), while the paramere blade of 
<taxonomicName box="[716,898,1664,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Metrocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guizhouensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[716,898,1664,1688]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">M. guizhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[904,994,1663,1688]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[904,994,1663,1688]" pageId="10" pageNumber="369">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is relatively stout and its subapical part is not curving (
